5mm [[Self propelled gun|SPG]] || || 36<ref name=armyrecog/> || \n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na]] || [[File:Firtina obus kzlsngr.JPG|170px]] || {{TUR}} || 155mm [[Self propelled gun|SPG]] || || 300<ref name=armyrecog/> || The T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na has a maximum firing range of 40 km depending on the type of ammunition and can fire up to 8 rounds for per minute. An upgraded version dubbed \"Firtina 2\" was to begin production in 2023, featuring improvement to range and rate of fire. The new vehicles were to be fitted with remote weapons stations capable of carrying 12.7mm, 7.62mm machine guns and 40&nbsp;mm grenade launchers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://savunmaveteknoloji.com/tskya-firtina-2ler-geliyor/|title=TSK'ya 'F\u0131rt\u0131na 2'ler geliyor|work=SVT {{!}} Savunma ve Teknoloji|accessdate=2017-07-13|language=tr-TR|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715122433/http://savunmaveteknoloji.com/tskya-firtina-2ler-geliyor/|archive-date=15 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> They will eventually replace all M44T, M107, M108, M109.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M52 Self Propelled Howitzer|M52]][[:es:Ob%C3%BAs_autopropulsado_M52|(Spanish)]] || [[File:M52 howitzer.JPG|170px]] || {{USA}}<br>{{GER}} || 155mm [[Self propelled gun|SPG]] || M52T || 362<ref name=armyrecog/> || Originally obtained from the US during the 1950s, by the 1990s the system became woefully obsolete so in 1995 Turkey began a modernization program which saw the SPG get a new turret, digital command and fire control, German 155-mm / L39 gun which replaced the original 105-mm gun, and a new more powerful German diesel engine replacing the original fuel guzzling petrol engine.<ref>{{cite web|title=M52T|url=http://www.military-today.com/artillery/m52t.htm|website=Military-Today.com|accessdate=1 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208180158/http://www.military-today.com/artillery/m52t.htm|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M44 Self Propelled Howitzer|M44]] || [[File:M44 - Vista fronto lateral.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}}<br>{{GER}} || 155mm [[Self propelled gun|SPG]] || M44T || 26<ref name=jamesron2>{{cite web|title=Weapons Transfers and Violations of the Laws of War in Turkey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b99dfVMJNRMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Weapons+Transfers+and+Violations+of+the+Laws+of+War+in+Turkey&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=jcwhU7PKDdCCyQOM-oCoAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|work=James Ron|publisher=Google|accessdate=13 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119175028/https://books.google.com/books?id=b99dfVMJNRMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Weapons+Transfers+and+Violations+of+the+Laws+of+War+in+Turkey&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=jcwhU7PKDdCCyQOM-oCoAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> || In 1986, 222 Turkish Army M44s were extensively upgraded with 36 caliber 155mm howitzers by [[Rheinmetall]] with an increased range of 24.7&nbsp;km. An MTU MB 833 Aa-501 V-6 water-cooled diesel developing 450&nbsp;hp at 2,300 rpm coupled to the original Allison CD-500-3 transmission via a ZF gearbox was fitted. There were numerous other improvements such as upgraded suspension, tracks and fire control and increased fuel capacity. The driver's position was moved into the hull. The last was delivered in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|title=M44 155mm Self-propelled gun|url=http://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/m44.htm|website=FAS.org|publisher=Federation of American Scientists|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> Withdrawn from active service.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M115 howitzer|M115]] || [[File:M115 203mm Howitzer Display in ORDC 20121013b.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}} || 203mm [[howitzer]] || || 162<ref name=armyrecog/> || \n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Panter (howitzer)|Panter]] || [[File:Panterrr.JPG|170px]] || {{TUR}} || 155mm [[howitzer]] || || 400<ref name=armyrecog/> || In the mid 1990s, and with the help of [[Singapore Technologies Kinetics]], Turkey developed a new 155mm howitzer - The Panther - which entered serial production in 2002.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M114 155 mm howitzer|M114]] || [[File:USArmy M114 howitzer.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}} || 155mm [[howitzer]] || M114A2 || 535<ref name=armyrecog/> \n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[MKEK Boran]]  || || {{TUR}} || 105mm [[field gun]] || || 7+ || MKE launched the 105 mm Air Transportable Light Towed Howitzer (BORAN) project to fulfill the operational requests of the Commando and Infantry units for Airborne Operations. The system can calculate its own position and identify targets without usual deployment procedures thanks to its modern command and fire control systems. It has a minimum range of 17 kilometers and 6400 NATO mils (360\u00b0) firing capability. The howitzer weights around 1800kg and can be airlifted with a medium-lift utility helicopter and deployed in a short time for fire missions. Based on [[L118]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Fire resistance tests. Fire dampers for air distribution systems|publisher=BSI British Standards|doi=10.3403/bsiso10294}}</ref><ref>https://www.defenceturk.net/105mm-boran</ref><ref>https://www.haber365.com.tr/teknoloji-haberleri/tskda-boran-donemi-h171406.html</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M101 howitzer|M101]] || [[File:M101-105mm-howitzer-camp-pendleton-20050326.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}} || 105mm [[field gun]] || M101A1 || 75<ref name=globalsecurity/> || \n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M116 howitzer|M116]] || [[File:Two M116 75mm Howitzers in Chengkungling 20111009.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}} || 75mm [[field gun]] || || ?<ref name=armyrecog/> || \n|}\n\n===Anti-aircraft===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#aabccc;\"\n!Model!!Image!!Origin!!Type!!Number!!Details\n|-\n|[[HISAR (surface to air missile system)|Hisar-A]]\n|[https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn%3AANd9GcSOTHGMVPlktTA0UowdgM62u3GaNWBrAU-atUU-v2Xrwib4FkX3]\n|{{TUR}}\n|Low-Altitude Air and Missile\nDefense System\n|x\n|Entered land forces inventory in 2020. \n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[At\u0131lgan PMADS]] ||[https://www.aselsan.com.tr/ATILGAN_3428.png]||{{TUR}}<br>{{USA}} || Short Range Air Defense || 150+<ref name=armyrecog/>|| First versions mounted on M113 APCs. When serial production begins first mounted on [[FNSS ACV-15]] chasis then mounted on [[FNSS ACV-19]]. Production Continues.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Z\u0131pk\u0131n PMADS]] ||[[File:Aselsanzipkin.JPG|170x170px]]||{{TUR}}<br>{{UK}} || Short Range Air Defense || 80+<ref name=armyrecog/>|| Mounted on Range Rover Defenders. Production Continues.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[FNSS ACV-30|ACV-30 Korkut]] || [https://www.savunmasanayi.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/korkut-sistemi.jpg] ||{{TUR}} || [[SPAAG]] || 13<ref>https://twitter.com/ssysfakb/status/1194168452677820417</ref>{{better|date=December 2019}} || Designed to replace to aging [[M42A1 Duster]] systems of the [[Turkish Armed Forces]], each Korkut system compromises of 1 command and control vehicle and 3 weapons platforms. The [[Turkish Armed Forces]] has ordered 40 weapons systems, deliveries are scheduled to complete in 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://savunmaveteknoloji.com/ilk-korkut-sistemi-teslim-edildi/|title=ilk-korkut-sistemi-teslim-edildI|accessdate=2016-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000224/http://savunmaveteknoloji.com/ilk-korkut-sistemi-teslim-edildi/|archive-date=2 February 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|ALKA DEWS\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.roketsan.com.tr/en/product/alka-directed-energy-weapon-system/|title=ALKA DIRECTED ENERGY WEAPON SYSTEM \u2013 Roketsan|website=www.roketsan.com.tr|accessdate=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n\n|[https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn%3AANd9GcTSil786jD1ykCFm2aMZ6W_G68da1cVhHHswha7-8FFFzlWWp7L]\n|{{TUR}}\n\n|UAV\n\nDefence\n|6\n|ALKA Directed Energy Weapon System (DEWS) neutralizes or totally destructs targets such as Improvised Explosive Devices (IED), mini/micro unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV), drones, mini/micro unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV) carrying a variety of payloads (camera, explosives, etc.) as well as swarm attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.roketsan.com.tr/en/product/alka-directed-energy-weapon-system/|title=ALKA DIRECTED ENERGY WEAPON SYSTEM \u2013 Roketsan|website=www.roketsan.com.tr|accessdate=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M42A1 Duster]] || [[File:M42-Duster-latrun-1.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}} || [[SPAAG]] || 262<ref name=armyrecog/><ref name=globalsecurity/> || In storage.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M45 Quadmount]] || [[File:M45 Quadmount, Pegasus Bridge, Normandy, France.JPG|170px]] || {{USA}} || AA Gun || 160<ref name=armyrecog/> || Used as ground support gun.\n|}\n\n===Engineering vehicles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#aabccc;\"\n!Model!!Image!!Origin!!Type!!Number!!Details\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[AZM\u0130M]] || [[File:Kunduz (2).jpg|170px]] || {{TUR}} || [[Armored bulldozer]] || x<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://savunmaveteknoloji.com/sirnakta-hendeklere-karsi-kunduz-operasyonu/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322142744/http://savunmaveteknoloji.com/sirnakta-hendeklere-karsi-kunduz-operasyonu/ |archive-date=22 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> || A Turkish license built variant of the American [[M9 ACE]].<ref>[http://www.armyrecognition.com/january_2013_army_military_defense_industry_news/fnss_has_delivered_the_azmim_aace_amphibious_armoured_earthmover_to_turksih_army_1401133.html AZMIM AACE Amphibious Armoured Earthmover delivered to Turkish Army] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118143200/http://www.armyrecognition.com/january_2013_army_military_defense_industry_news/fnss_has_delivered_the_azmim_aace_amphibious_armoured_earthmover_to_turksih_army_1401133.html |date=18 January 2013}} - Armyrecognition.com, 14 January 2013</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tosun (construction equipment)|TOSUN]]\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-to-export-military-vehicle-remote-control-system-128014|title=Turkey to exp