erschnellbr\u00fccke Leguan.jpg|170px]] || {{FRG}} || [[Armoured vehicle-launched bridge]] || 36<ref name=armyrecog/><ref name=globalsecurity/> || Bought from the German [[Bundeswehr]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deagel.com/news/Turkey-to-Purchase-36-Leopard-1-Based-Leguan-Bridge-Laying-Systems_n000005961.aspx|title=Turkey to Purchase 36 Leopard 2 Based Leguan Bridge Laying Systems|date=27 April 2009|accessdate=18 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222120016/http://www.deagel.com/news/Turkey-to-Purchase-36-Leopard-1-Based-Leguan-Bridge-Laying-Systems_n000005961.aspx|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M48 AVLB]] || [[File:BrLgPz M48 im Bundeswehrmuseum Dresden.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}}<br>{{FRG}} || [[Armoured vehicle-launched bridge]] || x<ref>https://books.google.com.tr/books?id=ctDPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=m48+avlb+turkey&source=bl&ots=1725uS9Kdf&sig=ACfU3U0fNNKRL6MXI0iQAYNshr6db59HLQ&hl=tr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjg37L3nLroAhWtyqYKHc6rDtAQ6AEwEnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=m48%20avlb%20turkey&f=false</ref> || On M48 Patton chassis.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M48A5T5 Tamay]] || [http://gallery.military.ir/albums/userpics/10206/M48T5_Tamay_ARV_IDEF_2005_ArmyRecognition_01.jpg] || {{USA}}<br>{{TUR}} || [[Armored recovery vehicle]] || 105<ref name=armyrecog/><ref name=globalsecurity/> || On M48 Patton chassis.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[MPG M4K]] || [https://www.trthaber.com/resimler/1048000/1048333.jpg] || {{TUR}} || Mine-resistant [[Armored recovery vehicle]] || x || Evaluations are completed. Commencing mass production.<ref>https://c4defence.com/Gundem/yerli-kurtarici-testleri-gecti/9240/1</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.milscint.com/en/mpgs-8x8-vehicle-for-the-recovery-of-tafs-armoured-vehicles/|title=MPG's 8\u00d78 Vehicle for the Recovery of TAF'S Armoured Vehicles \u2013 MSI Turkish Defence Review / MSI TDR Reference Magazine of Turkish Defence and Aviation Industry|website=www.milscint.com|language=tr-TR|accessdate=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M88 Recovery Vehicle|M88A1]] || [[File:\u00d6sterreichischer-Bergepanzer-M88-A1.JPG|170px]] || {{USA}} || [[Armored recovery vehicle]] || 33<ref name=armyrecog/><ref name=globalsecurity/> || On M60 Patton chassis.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Bergepanzer 2]] || [[File:Bergepanzer seite.jpg|170px]] || {{GER}} || [[Armored recovery vehicle]] || 20+<ref name=\"Bergepanzer L\u00e4nderabgaben\">Stefan Marx: ''Die Bergepanzer der Bundeswehr und die deutsche Bergetechnik'' (= ''Tankograd Milit\u00e4rfahrzeuge Spezialr'' Nr. 5005) Tankograd Publishing, 2004.</ref> || On Leopard 1 chassis.\n|-\n|MKEK POYRAZ\n|[https://www.trthaber.com/resimler/552000/552149.jpg]\n|{{TUR}}\n|Ammunition Resupply Vehicle\n|x\n|To maintain the firepower of the self propelled howitzers (SpH) in the battle field, fast supply of ammunition is very crucial. POYRAZ Ammunition Resupply Vehicle is capable of loading ammunition in supply area and transferring ammunition to the [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na|FIRTINA]] SpH within the required time and location in all kind of terrain and battlefield. POYRAZ Ammunition Resupply Vehicle has the necessary mobility and survivability capabilities for operation within the tactical operational environment of [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na|FIRTINA]] [[Self-propelled artillery|SpH]]. Therefore Ammunition Resupply Vehicles enhances the [[T-155 F\u0131rt\u0131na|FIRTINA]] SpH\u2019s mobility and provides capability for rapid deployment without being exposed to enemy counter-firing thus enables higher firing rate and shoot and scoot tactical requirements.\n\nAmmunition Transfer System which has been indigenously developed by [[ASELSAN]] performs loading and unloading of ammunition automatically by means of a four stage mechanism. Control of the mechanism is performed via servo control system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssb.gov.tr/urunkatalog/en/24/#zoom=z|title=aselsan info|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Utility vehicles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#aabccc;\"\n!Model!!Image!!Origin!!Number!!Details\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Jeep Wrangler|Wrangler]] || [[File:Jeep J8 IDET.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}}<br>{{TUR}} || 5,700<ref name=armyrecog/> || Produced under license by [[Otokar]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[Land Rover Defender|Defender]] ||[[File:Ex-Australian Army Land Rover.JPG|170px]]|| {{UK}}<br>{{TUR}} || 9,800<ref name=armyrecog/> || Produced under license by [[Otokar]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|[[Otokar Engerek|Engerek]]||[[File:Military parade in Baku on an Army Day25.jpg|170px]]||{{TUR}}|| 2,550 <ref name=\"armyrecog\" />|| Based on Land Rover Defender 110 with different variants such as Engerek anti-tank model.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[M151]] || [[File:AMG M151 A2 (1978) GB (owner Gavin Broad).JPG|170px]] || {{USA}} || x<ref name=militaryfactory2>{{cite web|title=M151 MUTT|url=http://www.militaryfactory.com/armor/detail.asp?armor_id=117|website=Military Factory|accessdate=4 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606202616/http://www.militaryfactory.com/armor/detail.asp?armor_id=117|archive-date=6 June 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> || Bought from US surplus. Also some M825 M40 carriers.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| [[CJ-3B]] || [[File:Willyjeep01.jpg|170px]] || {{USA}}<br>{{TUR}} || x<ref name=\"military-vehicle-photos\">{{cite web|url=http://www.military-vehicle-photos.com/picture/number9536.asp|title=Military Vehicle Photos - Jeep - Republic Day Parade|publisher=military-vehicle-photos.com|accessdate=5 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721001038/http://www.military-vehicle-photos.com/picture/number9536.asp|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"cj3b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cj3b.info/World/TurkeyMilitary.html|title=Turkish Army Jeeps on The CJ3B Page|publisher=cj3b.info|accessdate=5 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/2015