| <center>4\u20131</center> || | [[1950 FIFA World Cup]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|20\n| | 7 September 1950 || | [[Helsinki]], Finland || | {{fb|FIN}} || <center>1\u20130</center> || | <center>2\u20133</center> || rowspan=7 | Friendly \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|21\n| | 10 September 1950 || | [[Copenhagen]], Denmark || | {{fb|DEN}} || <center>2\u20130</center> || | <center>4\u20131</center> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|22\n| rowspan=2 | 24 June 1951 || rowspan=2 | [[Belgrade]], Yugoslavia || rowspan=2 |{{fb|SUI}} ||align=center| <center>1\u20130</center> || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 7\u20133 \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|23\n| <center>6\u20130</center>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|24\n| rowspan=2 | 23 August 1951 || rowspan=2 | [[Oslo]], Norway || rowspan=2 |{{fb|NOR}} ||align=center| <center>2\u20130</center> || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\u20132 \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|25\n| <center>4\u20130</center>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|26\n| | 2 September 1951 || | [[Belgrade]], Yugoslavia || | {{fb|SWE}} || <center>1\u20131</center> || | <center>2\u20131</center> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|27\n| | 20 July 1952 || | [[Tampere]], Finland || | {{fb|Soviet Union}} || <center>4\u20130</center> || | <center>5\u20135</center> || rowspan=3 | [[Football at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952 Summer Olympics]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|28\n| | 22 July 1952 || | [[Tampere]], Finland || | {{fb|Soviet Union}} || <center>2\u20131</center> || | <center>3\u20131</center> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|29\n| | 25 July 1952 || | [[Helsinki]], Finland || | {{fb|DEN}} || <center>4\u20131</center> || | <center>5\u20133</center> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|30\n| rowspan=3 | 21 September 1952 || rowspan=3 | [[Belgrade]], Yugoslavia || rowspan=3 |{{fb|AUT}} ||align=center| <center>1\u20130</center> || rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\u20132 || rowspan=9 | Friendly \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|31\n| <center>2\u20130</center>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|32\n| <center>4\u20132</center>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|33\n| | 21 December 1952 || | [[Ludwigshafen]], West Germany || | {{fb|FRG}} || <center>2\u20131</center> || | <center>2\u20133</center> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|34\n| | 26 September 1954 || | [[Saarbr\u00fccken]], Saarland || | {{fb|SAA}} || <center>2\u20131</center> || | <center>5\u20131</center> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|35\n| | 3 October 1954 || | [[Vienna]], Austria || | {{fb|AUT}} || <center>2\u20131</center> || | <center>2\u20132</center> \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|36\n| rowspan=3 | 17 October 1954 || rowspan=3 | [[Sarajevo]], Yugoslavia || rowspan=3 |{{fb|TUR}} ||align=center| <center>1\u20130</center> || rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\u20131 \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|37\n| <center>2\u20130</center>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|38\n| <center>4\u20130</center>\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===As player===\n;FK Partizan\n* [[Yugoslav First League]] (2): [[1946\u201347 Yugoslav First League|1946\u201347]], [[1948\u201349 Yugoslav First League|1948\u201349]]\n* [[Yugoslav Cup]] (4): 1947, 1952, 1954, 1957\n\n;Yugoslavia\n* [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympic Silver Medal]] (2): [[Football at the 1948 Summer Olympics|1948]], [[Football at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952]]\n\n;Individual\n* Yugoslav First League top scorer (2): [[1945 Yugoslav First League|1945]], [[1953\u201354 Yugoslav First League|1953\u201354]]\n\n;Records\n* [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia all-time top scorer]]: 38 goals<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reprezentacija.rs/index.php/statistika/najbolji-strelci|title=Stjepan Bobek najbolji strelac|date=25 September 2013|work=www.reprezentacija.rs|language=sr}}</ref>\n\n===As manager===\n;FK Partizan\n* [[Yugoslav First League]] (3): [[1960\u201361 Yugoslav First League|1960\u201361]], [[1961\u201362 Yugoslav First League|1961\u201362]], [[1962\u201363 Yugoslav First League|1962\u201363]]\n\n;Panathinaikos\n* [[Superleague Greece|Greek Championship]] (2): [[1963\u201364 Alpha Ethniki|1963\u201364]], [[1964\u201365 Alpha Ethniki|1964\u201365]]\n* [[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]] (1): [[1966\u201367 Greek Cup|1967]]\n\n;Vardar\n* [[Yugoslav Second League]] (1): 1978\u201379\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Stjepan Bobek}}\n* {{FIFA player|174410}}\n* {{NFT player|pid=19912}}\n* [http://www.reprezentacija.rs/bobek-stjepan/ Stjepan Bobek international stats] at Reprezentacija.rs {{in lang|sr}}\n\n{{Yugoslav First League top scorers}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Stjepan Bobek international tournaments\n|list1=\n{{Yugoslavia football squad 1948 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Yugoslavia squad 1950 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Yugoslavia football squad 1952 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Yugoslavia squad 1954 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Stjepan Bobek managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Legia Warszawa managers}}\n{{FK Partizan managers}}\n{{Panathinaikos FC managers}}\n{{Olympiacos managers}}\n{{Altay S.K. managers}}\n{{Dinamo Zagreb managers}}\n{{Panetolikos F.C. managers}}\n{{FK Vardar managers}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bobek, Stjepan}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Croatian footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Croats of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriates in Poland]]\n[[Category:Croatian football managers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslavia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav football managers]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:H\u0160K Gra\u0111anski Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:FK Partizan players]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:1950 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1954 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece managers]]\n[[Category:Legia Warsaw managers]]\n[[Category:FK Partizan managers]]\n[[Category:Panathinaikos F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb managers]]\n[[Category:Panetolikos F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis managers]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Poland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:FK Vardar managers]]\n[[Category:Altay S.K. managers]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Burials at Belgrade New Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Stjepan Bobek\n| image               = Stjepan Bobek.jpg\n| image_size          = 195px\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1923|12|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Zagreb]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Kingdom of SCS]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2010|8|22|1923|12|3|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]]\n| height              =\n| position            = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1         = 1936\u20131938 | youthclubs1  = H\u0160K Derbi\n| youthyears2         = 1938\u20131942 | youthclubs2  = \u0160K Zagreb\n| youthyears3         = 1942\u20131944 | youthclubs3  = H\u0160K Li\u010danin\n| years1              = 1942      | clubs1 = [[VfB Admira Wacker M\u00f6dling|Admira Wacker]] | caps1 = 8   | goals1 = 7\n| years2              = 1944\u20131945 | clubs2 = [[Gra\u0111anski Zagreb]]                        | caps2 = 15  | goals2 = 13\n| years3              = 1945\u20131959 | clubs3 = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]]                    | caps3 = 198 | goals3 = 121\n| totalcaps           = 221\n| totalgoals          = 141\n| nationalyears1      = 1943\u20131945\n| nationalteam1       = [[Croatia national football team|Croatia U21]]\n| nationalcaps1       = ?\n| nationalgoals1      = ?\n| nationalyears2      = 1946\u20131956\n| nationalteam2       = [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]]\n| nationalcaps2       = 63\n| nationalgoals2      = 38\n| medaltemplates      =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Association football|Football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{YUG}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}{{MedalSilver | [[1948 Summer Olympics|1948 London]] | [[Football at the 1948 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1952 Summer Olympics|1952 Helsinki]]|[[Football at the 1952 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n| manageryears1       = 1959       | managerclubs1 = [[Legia Warszawa|Legia Warsaw]]\n| manageryears2       = 1960\u20131963  | managerclubs2 = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n| manageryears3       = 1963       | managerclubs3 = [[Legia Warszawa|Legia Warsaw]]\n| manageryears4       = 1963\u20131967  | managerclubs4 = [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]\n| manageryears5       = 1967\u20131969  | managerclubs5 = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n| manageryears6       = 1969\u20131970  | managerclubs6 = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n| manageryears7       = 1970       | managerclubs7 = [[Altay S.K.|Altay]]\n| manageryears8       = 1972       | managerclubs8 = [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n| manageryears9       = 1974\u20131975  | managerclubs9 = [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]\n| manageryears10      = 1975\u20131976 | managerclubs10 = [[Panetolikos F.C.]]\n| manageryears11      = 1976\u20131978  | managerclubs11 = [[Esp\u00e9rance Sportive de Tunis|Esp\u00e9rance]]\n| manageryears12      = 1978\u20131981  | managerclubs12 = [[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n| manageryears13      =            | managerclubs13 = [[FK Zemun|Zemun]]\n}}\n\n'''Stjepan Bobek''' ({{IPA-sh|stj\u00eapa\u02d0n b\u01d2bek|pron}}; 3 December 1923 \u2013 22 August 2010) was a Croatian and [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] professional [[Association football|football]] [[Forward (association football)|striker]] and later [[Manager (association football)|football manager]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arhiva.kurir-info.rs/Arhiva/2006/oktobar/29/SP-01-29102006.shtml|title=INTERVJU: Stjepan Bobek. Srbi su sjajni|language=Serbian|publisher=kurir-info.rs|date=29 October 2006|accessdate=1 May 2013|quote=Ja sam Hrvat, normalno, ali istina je da sam zavoleo Srbiju.}}</ref>\n\nUsually a forward or attacking midfielder, Bobek was renowned for his technique, vision and goalscoring ability and is commonly regarded as one of Yugoslavia's greatest players. He is remembered for his time at the Serbian side [[FK Partizan|Partizan Belgrade]], where he moved to following the end of [[World War II]]. He played for Partizan between 1945 and 1959 helping them win two [[Yugoslav First League]] titles and four [[Yugoslav Cup]]s, and was named the club's greatest player in history in 1995. Internationally, he is the all-time top scorer for the [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia national team]], scoring 38 goals in 63 appearances between 1946 and 1956, and was member of Yugoslav squads which won two Olympic silver medals (in 1948 and 1952) and played in two [[FIFA World Cup]]s (in 1950 and 1954).\n\nAfter retiring from active football in 1959, he was a successful manager, winning Yugoslav and Greek national titles with Partizan and [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBobek was born in Zagreb and started playing at the age of 13 for Viktorija, a lower league club, using his brother's registration papers. When he was 20 he became the center-forward of [[Gra\u0111anski Zagreb]].\n\nHe also played for [[Croatia national football team|Croatia U21]] between 1943 and 1945.<ref>[https://www.tportal.hr/sport/clanak/vosini-navijaci-izvrijedali-nedavno-preminulog-bobeka-20101002/print Vo\u0161ini navija\u010di izvrije\u0111ali nedavno preminulog Bobeka]</ref><ref>[https://www.kurir.rs/sport/fudbal/3107631/legenda-crno-belih-otkrila-manje-poznate-detalje-iz-zivota-evo-kako-sam-izbegao-odlazak-u-pavelicevu-ustasku-vojsku-ndh-plakao-sam-kad-sam-dolazio-u-partizan-video]</ref><ref>[http://informer.rs/sport/partizan/261193/hrvati-partizan-nas-treci-najveci-klub-napravili--potpuno-zatrli-fudbal-zagrebu]</ref>\n\nHe was the top scorer of the [[Yugoslav First League]] twice, in [[1945 Yugoslav First League|1945]] (25 goals) and [[1953\u201354 Yugoslav First League|1954]] (21 goals).\n\n===Partizan===\nHe came to FK Partizan in 1945 and played for them until 1958. During his time in Partizan, he played 468 games and scored 403 goals, still holding the club record. Bobek won two Yugoslav League titles and the [[Yugoslav Cup]] four times. \n\nHe scored his first goals in official matches, on 1 September 1946, in 2nd leg of [[1946\u201347 Yugoslav First League|Yugoslav First League]]. He scored a twice in a 6\u20131 home victory over [[FK Budu\u0107nost Titograd|Budu\u0107nost]]. On 5 January 1947, Bobek scored his first goal, in first [[Eternal derby (Serbia)|Eternal derby]] against [[Red Star Belgrade]], in 3\u20134 home defeat. That was also first goal in Derby, scored by Partizan player, because previous two was a own goals. On 8 June 1947 in a league match played in [[Ni\u0161]] between [[14. Oktobar Ni\u0161|14. Oktobar]] and [[FK Partizan]] (1\u201310), Bobek scored eight goals \u2013 an absolute record that has never been broken until the end of Yugoslav First League or its successor leagues. He scored 25 goals in 22 matches in first season of First League of SFR Yugoslavia and also won first title and gave a great contribution. \n\nIn May 1951, Partizan played three friendly matches in England. The first match was played on 9 May, against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and Partizan beat them 3\u20132. Bobek played brilliant and scored two goals in great victory. Three days later he again played brilliant match and scored a one goal in second Partizan's victory, over English teams. The result was the same like three days before, but this time against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. One month later, he scored a twice in one of the biggest victories in Eternal Derby, in a 6\u20131 home victory over Red Star. In November of that year, Bobek scored a six goals against [[FK Sloboda U\u017eice|Sloboda Titovo U\u017eice]], in a ''qualifying round'' of Yugoslav Cup, in a 11\u20131 away victory. A week later, he also set a record in Yugoslavian Cup. He scored eight goals in 15\u20130 home victory over [[FK Sloga Petrovac na Mlavi|Sloga Petrovac na Mlavi]].\n\nOn 29 November 1952, Bobek scored a goal in a 6\u20130 victory over a arch rival Red Star Belgrade in the ''final'' of Yugoslav Cup. A three weeks before, he scored a hat-trick in a 4\u20130 home victory over one of the best [[West Germany|German]] teams at that time \u2013 [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]].\n\nBobek continued with great perfomances in next seasons. He scored a goal in biggest victory ever in Eternal Derby. After four minutes, he scored first goal on the match, in a 7\u20131 home victory over Red Star, on 6 December 1953. On 11 April 1954, he scored a four goals in 8\u20130 home league victory over [[FK Rabotni\u010dki|Rabotni\u010dki]].\n\nTwo years later after winning second Yugoslav Cup, he won a third. Again Partizan beat Red Star, but this time 4\u20131 and Bobek again scored one goal. \n\nOn 4 September 1955, Bobek scored a first goal in first ever match of [[European Cup]]. Partizan draw (3\u20133) with [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]], in [[Lisbon]]. He played all four matches in [[1955\u201356 European Cup]]. Should be noted a legendary victory 3\u20130 over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in ''quarter-finals''.\n\n===National team===\nBobek made his debut for the [[Yugoslavia national football team]] on 9 May 1946, at [[Letn\u00e1 Stadium]] in 2\u20130 win over [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] in [[Prague]]. That was a first ever match of [[SFR Yugoslavia]]. He scored his first goal in national team, against Czechoslovakia, in [[Belgrade]], on 29 September 1946, in 4\u20132 home victory. That was first match of national team in SFR Yugoslavia.\n\nBobek won silver medal with Yugoslavia, on [[Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]], in [[1948 Summer Olympics|London 1948]]. He scored four goals in four matches. In every match, he scored one goal. One goal against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] in ''first round'' (6\u20131 victory), [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in ''quarter-finals'' (3\u20131 victory), [[Great Britain Olympic football team|Great Britain]] in ''semi-finals'' (3\u20131 victory) and one against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] in ''final'' (1\u20133 defeat).\n\nBobek played on [[1950 FIFA World Cup]], in [[Brazil]] (where he scored one goal in the 4\u20131 win over [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]]). \n\nOn 21 September 1952, Bobek scored his first [[hat-trick]] in national team, in 4\u20132 home victory over [[Austria national football team|Austria]]. Two years later, he scored his second hat-trick in national team, in 5\u20131 home victory over Turkey. That was his last goals for ''The Blues''.\n\nBobek played on World Cup in [[1954 FIFA World Cup|Switzerland 1954]]. He also played in two [[Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]], in [[1948 Summer Olympics|London 1948]] (where he scored 4 goals and Yugoslavia won the silver medal) and in [[1952 Summer Olympics|Helsinki 1952]] (he scored three goals in the tournament and Yugoslavia won the Silver Medal).\n\n==Managerial career==\nAfter retiring from the play, he became a football manager. In 1959 he became the coach of [[Legia Warszawa|CWKS Warszawa]] in [[Poland]], moving back to Yugoslavia the next season to manage FK Partizan. The team won three successive Yugoslav League championships under him, after which he was replaced by Kiril Simonovski in 1963. In 1964 he had another spell in Warsaw, and then he moved to [[Greece]] where he led [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] in the 1960s. In the 1967\u201368 and 1968\u201369 seasons, he again returned to manage FK Partizan. In 1970, he moved to [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]. In 1972, he was the manager of [[Dinamo Zagreb]] and during 1974\u201375 season of Panathinaikos for a second time, but without former success. He also coached [[Vardar Skopje]] and led them to [[1978\u201379 Yugoslav Second League]]'s East Division title and subsequent promotion to the First League.\n\nIn 1995, he was named the all-time greatest player of Partizan Belgrade.<ref name=\"seebiz\">{{cite news|url=http://www.seebiz.eu/hr/karijere/stjepan-bobek,-jedan-od-najvecih-hrvatskih-nogometasa,-umro-u-87.-godini,89306.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827004101/http://www.seebiz.eu/hr/karijere/stjepan-bobek,-jedan-od-najvecih-hrvatskih-nogometasa,-umro-u-87.-godini,89306.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 August 2010|title=IN MEMORIAM: Stjepan Bobek, jedan od najve\u0107ih hrvatskih nogometa\u0161a, umro u 87. godini|date=22 August 2010|work=SEEbiz.eu|language=Croatian|access-date=22 August 2010}}</ref> In 2009, Bobek's biography written by sports journalist Fredi Kramer was published.<ref name=\"kramer\">{{cite news|url=http://web2.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Nogomet/tabid/84/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/42227/Default.aspx|title=U Beogradu predstavljena monografija o Stjepanu Bobeku|date=15 February 2009|work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|language=Croatian|access-date=22 August 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721102813/http://web2.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Nogomet/tabid/84/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/42227/Default.aspx|archive-date=21 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nBobek died shortly after midnight on 22 August 2010 in Belgrade.<ref name=\"seebiz\"/> He is interred in the [[Belgrade New Cemetery#Alley of Distinguished Citizens|Alley of Distinguished Citizens]] in the [[Belgrade New Cemetery]].<ref>[http://graves.mf.uni-lj.si/graves/885/stjepan-bobek International graves]</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|League\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"13\"|[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|rowspan=\"13\"|[[Yugoslav First League]]\n|[[1946\u201347 Yugoslav First League|1946\u201347]]\n|23||24||0||0||23||24\n|-\n|[[1947\u201348 Yugoslav First League|1947\u201348]]\n|12||4||0||0||12||4\n|-\n|[[1948\u201349 Yugoslav First League|1948\u201349]]\n|17||13||0||0||17||13\n|-\n|[[1950 Yugoslav First League|1950]]\n|17||6||0||0||17||6\n|-\n|[[1951 Yugoslav First League|1951]]\n|21||9||0||0||21||9\n|-\n|[[1952 Yugoslav First League|1952]]\n|9||9||0||0||9||9\n|-\n|[[1952\u201353 Yugoslav First League|1952\u201353]]\n|12||7||0||0||12||7\n|-\n|[[1953\u201354 Yugoslav First League|1953\u201354]]\n|23||21||0||0||23||21\n|-\n|[[1954\u201355 Yugoslav First League|1954\u201355]]\n|18||16||0||0||18||16\n|-\n|[[1955\u201356 Yugoslav First League|1955\u201356]]\n|17||9||4||1||21||10\n|-\n|[[1956\u201357 Yugoslav First League|1956\u201357]]\n|15||3||0||0||15||3\n|-\n|[[1957\u201358 Yugoslav First League|1957\u201358]]\n|9||0||0||0||9||0\n|-\n|[[1958\u201359 Yugoslav First League|1958\u201359]]\n|5||0||0||0||5||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!198!!121!!4!!1!!202!!122\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+List of international goals scored by Stjepan Bobek\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | No. \n! scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"date\" | Date \n! scope=\"col\" | Venue \n! scope=\"col\" | Opponent \n! scope=\"col\" | Score \n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | Competition \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|1\n|| 29 September 1946 || [[Belgrade]], Yugoslavia || {{fb|TCH}} || <center>4\u20131</center> || <center>4\u20132</center> || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|2\n| | 7 October 1946 || | [[Tirana]], Albania || {{fb|Albania|1946}} || <center>2\u20132</center> || <center>3\u20132</center> || [[Balkan Cup]]\n|-\n!scope=